The paper discusses the combination of sub-structural features and defeasibility aspects to handle conflicting information in the context of energy management and business process management. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category, as it deals with knowledge representation and reasoning. The use of linear logic and defeasible logic also suggests that the paper may belong to the Logic in Computer Science (cs.LO) sub-category. The focus on business processes suggests that the paper may also belong to the Software Engineering (cs.SE) sub-category. The use of sub-structural features may suggest that the paper belongs to the Programming Languages (cs.PL) sub-category, while the use of logic may suggest that it belongs to the Computational Complexity (cs.CC) sub-category.
